Matthis did not wake hungry, like usual. His stomach did not hurt. But his bones did. 

He washed his face in the basin. He checked the box under the table that held the basin. He found little crumbs of sage and juniper. He had hoped to light some this morning to cut the smell of rot.

He knelt beside his cot and fished under it with his hands. He pulled out a small pouch of coins and placed them in his satchel. 

Outside, the wizard stood in the same spot as the night before. But its sockets pointed at Matthis. He froze. The black skull slowly turned its head away. It watched the cages. 

Matthis shivered. 

He spread the ash where he had burned the wizard's old flesh and clothing. It was cold. Then he stopped along the cages. The skeletons stirred, but he stayed out of their attack range. The locking pins had worn down from rust. He took a step toward a skeleton. It sprang forward and clawed at him. He didn't like the way the pins rattled. 

He adjusted his satchel and made his way to the square. The sky was watery gray this morning. He stopped. He looked back. 

The black skeleton made no move to follow him. 

"Oi," he called. 

The black skull turned. It looked at him. Then it slowly turned back. It stared at the gibbets. 

Matthis walked backward. He stopped. He turned and walked a few feet and looked back. 

The wizard did not move.

--

The smithy smelled of coal fire, heat, and oiled metal. The smith pumped a bellows larger than him. A leather apron blanketed his round belly. His wide beard curled down to his collarbone. His arms looked as hard as the metal he forged. 

"Locking pins?" he asked when Matthis approached. He drew red metal out of the stone forged and hammered it.

"Goodman Foster --"

"Oh, quit that. Just call me Foss."

Matthis blinked. "How did you know?"

"Iron rusts." He set the metal in the fire and placed the tongs on the anvil. "So how many are weak? All seven?"

Matthis stared. Not two days ago, there were eight gibbets. 

Foss grunted. "I saw the eighth one after the mine rumble. Turned to thread? Wizard's magic. Odd that."

Matthis nodded. "I thought nails would do the trick this time. To replace the pins."

Foss grunted. "They would." He patted his anvil with his gloved hand. "Right tool, right job, though."

Matthis didn't have a response to that. So he pulled his money pouch from his satchel. But Foss waved it away. 

"Come back tomorrow. We'll talk weights and scales after you see your new pins."

Foss gathered the tongs and returned to the forge. He pumped the bellows. Matthis closed his mouth and dropped the money pouch in his satchel. 

"The bars on those gibbets look a bit rusted, too. Imagine trying to treat them with a skeleton scratching at you."

"You'll get them back one day," Matthis promised. "The skeletons will not hang there forever." He wasn't sure he had convinced himself.

"Keep a sharp eye on them. If the rust isn't too deep, something might be saved."

The forge roared with every pump of the bellows. The smith bounced his hammer on the anvil. The metal sang with the morning birds.

Foss said, "Good day," as Matthis walked away. 

--

Matthis knocked on the apothecary door. For the third time. He tapped his foot. The sky had turned iron gray.

"Hold on, hold on," said a muffled voice inside. "Dawn does not crack like a whip for all of us, you know."

A white head poked out of the door. A pair of bloodshot eyes turned up to Matthis.

"Sorry to wake you, Master Phineas."

"Well." The man blinked at him like an owl. "At least you're polite. Vinegar?" He turned inside and didn't bother to open the door any wider. 

Matthis hesitated and walked into a wall of scents that made his eyes burn. One wall was made entirely of shelves, floor to ceiling. Bundles of herbs wrapped in cloth, beeswax candles, bottles of every size. He felt a bit dizzy. 

"And sage and juniper."

"You'll want wormwood as well. It keeps flies away. You'll find that useful, in your work." 

Phineas ducked behind the counter. It was laden with three differently sized mortars and pestles. He emerged with a stool, which he used to climb to a shelf Matthis could have reached. But Matthis knew better than to touch anything.

Matthis noticed a set of bottles that he recognized as laudanum. He had needed some two winters ago. 

Phineas returned to the counter with three sets of herbs tied with string, a bottle, and a bundle of cloth.

"You'll want lye soap as well. It's tough on the skin, so be careful with it." Phineas blinked with his eyebrows. 

Matthis did need soap, so he didn't argue. He pulled out his coins and counted a few into Phineas' hand. 

The little man nodded. "That's the price we negotiated last time. Good enough. Come back after dawn next time."

Matthis had just enough time to place his items in his satchel before the door closed behind him. He smiled to himself and shook his head. Always the same, Master Phineas. 

Thunder rolled overhead. The air stilled. Matthis pulled his coat tighter around him.

--